297
00:16:28,687 --> 00:16:31,713
The Crime of Government
Against the Negro People."

298
00:16:33,459 --> 00:16:36,792
He chose the U.N.
because it would have

299
00:16:36,862 --> 00:16:39,729
provided
a worldwide voice.

300
00:16:39,798 --> 00:16:42,562
MAN: Robeson was pointing
to the fact that

301
00:16:42,634 --> 00:16:47,401
in this country,
blacks were still living

302
00:16:47,473 --> 00:16:50,271
in desperate circumstances,

303
00:16:50,342 --> 00:16:51,809
and that
the federal government,

304
00:16:51,877 --> 00:16:53,367
let alone
the state governments,

305
00:16:53,445 --> 00:16:55,242
were doing almost
nothing about it.

306
00:16:57,383 --> 00:17:01,183
He insisted that
economic deprivations

307
00:17:01,253 --> 00:17:05,212
were just as destructive
of human life

308
00:17:05,290 --> 00:17:09,590
as were the overt
policies of
a state regime,

309
00:17:09,661 --> 00:17:11,492
like Hitler
and the Jews.

310
00:17:13,999 --> 00:17:17,696
GATES: Robeson thought that
only a Communist revolution

311
00:17:17,770 --> 00:17:21,570
could solve the problem
of racial discrimination
in America.

312
00:17:22,875 --> 00:17:26,470
Most other
black leaders disagreed.

313
00:17:26,545 --> 00:17:30,572
DUBERMAN: At that point in time,
the black leadership
in this country

314
00:17:30,649 --> 00:17:35,245
still felt that they
had to present themselves

315
00:17:35,320 --> 00:17:37,948
as good, patriotic Americans,

316
00:17:38,023 --> 00:17:42,084
and there was no room for
Robeson in that scenario.

317
00:17:43,595 --> 00:17:45,256
GATES: For more than a decade,

318
00:17:45,330 --> 00:17:50,131
the NAACP had been mounting
a pain staking legal effort

319
00:17:50,202 --> 00:17:53,365
to dismantle Jim Crow.

320
00:17:53,439 --> 00:17:57,671
Robeson, to them, was
a dangerous gadﬂy.

321
00:17:57,743 --> 00:18:00,735
How important do you
think Robeson was

322
00:18:00,813 --> 00:18:03,441
to the creation
of the modern
civil rights movement?

323
00:18:03,515 --> 00:18:06,973
Once the modem
civil rights
movement got going,

324
00:18:07,052 --> 00:18:10,146
he was not regarded
as one of the great

325
00:18:10,222 --> 00:18:13,885
precursors, which,
in fact, he was.

326
00:18:13,959 --> 00:18:16,553
He was always
on the cutting edge

327
00:18:16,628 --> 00:18:18,823
of racial justice.

328
00:18:18,897 --> 00:18:21,957
GATES: Robeson introduced
a tactic that,

329
00:18:22,034 --> 00:18:24,935
when the time was right,
others would repeat.

330
00:18:26,638 --> 00:18:30,438
His public shaming of the United
