331
00:18:30,509 --> 00:18:32,943
would prove to be a key strategy

332
00:18:33,011 --> 00:18:37,505
used by others in the mass
movement to come,

333
00:18:37,583 --> 00:18:40,814
a movement that would
ultimately sweep the nation,

334
00:18:40,886 --> 00:18:43,821
but that began
in the American South.

335
00:18:59,671 --> 00:19:02,799
The first major battle of
the civil rights movement

336
00:19:02,875 --> 00:19:06,504
began on a city bus
in Montgomery, Alabama.

337
00:19:08,614 --> 00:19:13,142
GATES, VOICE-OVER: On this bus,
on December 1,1955,

338
00:19:13,218 --> 00:19:18,349
Rosa Parks refused to give up
her seat to a white man.

339
00:19:18,423 --> 00:19:23,190
The battle over this very seat
launched a revolution,

340
00:19:23,262 --> 00:19:25,628
and Rosa Parks became its icon.

341
00:19:27,499 --> 00:19:29,694
Civil rights leaders
had long been looking

342
00:19:29,768 --> 00:19:33,534
for the ideal candidate
to challenge segregation

343
00:19:33,605 --> 00:19:35,596
on public buses.

344
00:19:35,674 --> 00:19:38,370
Mrs. Parks
fit the bill perfectly.

345
00:19:40,145 --> 00:19:42,739
LEWIS: She, of course,
doesn't come out of nowhere.

346
00:19:42,814 --> 00:19:46,409
There had been
trial runs of 3 women

347
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:51,980
who were thought to be
not quite perfect.

348
00:19:52,057 --> 00:19:55,458
So, the stars were
aligned with Rosa Parks,

349
00:19:55,527 --> 00:19:59,623
a wonderfully composed
and courageous woman.

350
00:20:01,066 --> 00:20:03,557
GATES: Rosa Parks'
dignified manner

351
00:20:03,635 --> 00:20:07,196
masked her long history
as a tenacious activist.

352
00:20:08,740 --> 00:20:14,201
LEWIS: She had gone to
the Highlander Folk School
in Tennessee,

353
00:20:14,279 --> 00:20:18,238
the cockpit for
much labor organizing

354
00:20:18,317 --> 00:20:20,114
and civil rights planning,

355
00:20:20,185 --> 00:20:22,710
and <i>so</i> she had, in a <i>sense,</i>

356
00:20:22,788 --> 00:20:26,656
already had
a dress rehearsal experience.

357
00:20:26,725 --> 00:20:28,625
MAN: I heard somebody
said once that

358
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:33,393
when Rosa Parks sat down,
black people stood up.

359
00:20:33,465 --> 00:20:34,932
Ha ha! That's right.

360
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,264
She democratized
the movement.

361
00:20:38,704 --> 00:20:42,162
It became a people's
movement at all levels.

362
00:20:46,245 --> 00:20:48,679
GATES: Inspired by
Parks' example,

363
00:20:48,747 --> 00:20:50,840
Montgomery's black community

364
00:20:50,916 --> 00:20:53,077
opted to walk to their jobs

365
00:20:53,151 --> 00:20:55,517
instead of riding
the city's buses.

366
00:20:57,422 --> 00:20:58,684
JORDAN:There are
many great lines

367
00:20:58,757 --> 00:21:00,520
in the civil rights movement,

368
00:21:00,592 --> 00:21:04,460
but there is none better

369
00:21:04,529 --> 00:21:08,488
than the black maid Wm),
in the second week, said,

370
00:21:08,567 --> 00:21:13,231
"My feets are tired
but my soul is rested."

371
00:21:13,305 --> 00:21:16,433
That was a statement
of inspiration,

372
00:21:16,508 --> 00:21:20,000
and it was
a statement saying,

373
00:21:20,078 --> 00:21:21,875
"Let's get on with it."

374
00:21:26,084 --> 00:21:30,043
KING: 90% at least of
the regular Negro bus passengers

375
00:21:30,122 --> 00:21:33,717
are staying off the buses,
and we plan to continue

376
00:21:33,792 --> 00:21:35,919
until something is done.

377
00:21:35,994 --> 00:21:38,394
GATES: The boycott effort
came to be led

378
00:21:38,463 --> 00:21:42,365
by an unknown young minister
from Atlanta.

379
00:21:42,434 --> 00:21:45,301
26-year-old
Martin Luther King, Jr.

380
00:21:45,370 --> 00:21:49,329
