00:41:00,958 --> 00:41:05,691
the philosophic meaning
of nonviolence.

731
00:41:05,763 --> 00:41:07,424
It took us a while
to do that.

732
00:41:07,498 --> 00:41:09,056
So King was
ahead of you.

733
00:41:09,133 --> 00:41:11,601
Yeah, in essence.
Ah.

734
00:41:11,669 --> 00:41:16,766
But I think by '63
in Detroit,

735
00:41:16,841 --> 00:41:20,072
we were much more...

736
00:41:20,144 --> 00:41:23,477
infatuated with Malcolm,

737
00:41:23,547 --> 00:41:25,378
and we were thin king

738
00:41:25,449 --> 00:41:29,476
we had to redefine ourselves,

739
00:41:29,553 --> 00:41:32,147
that we had to become
more self-reliant,

740
00:41:32,223 --> 00:41:34,817
more self-determining,

741
00:41:34,892 --> 00:41:37,053
that we had to create
a new dream.

742
00:41:40,831 --> 00:41:43,561
[Sirens]

743
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:46,228
[Screaming and shouting]

744
00:41:46,303 --> 00:41:48,567
GATES: For the next
few years, however,

745
00:41:48,639 --> 00:41:50,971
Dr. King's nonviolent
civil disobedience

746
00:41:51,041 --> 00:41:54,499
continued to dominate
civil rights strategy

747
00:41:54,578 --> 00:41:57,479
as the movement spread
across the country.

748
00:42:04,088 --> 00:42:06,613
PRESIDENT JOHNSON: I am about
to sign into law

749
00:42:06,690 --> 00:42:09,921
the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

750
00:42:09,994 --> 00:42:12,519
GATES: The more civil rights
protesters suffered violence

751
00:42:12,596 --> 00:42:14,086
and even death,

752
00:42:14,164 --> 00:42:17,327
the clearer the justice
of their cause became

753
00:42:17,401 --> 00:42:20,427
and the harder it became
to ignore.

754
00:42:24,909 --> 00:42:26,968
The civil rights movement
reached a climax

755
00:42:27,044 --> 00:42:30,480
on March 7, 1965,

756
00:42:30,548 --> 00:42:32,948
when a peaceful march
for voting rights

757
00:42:33,017 --> 00:42:35,645
from Selma to Montgomery
turned into

758
00:42:35,719 --> 00:42:39,450
what would become known
as Bloody Sunday.

759
00:42:39,523 --> 00:42:42,583
We're marching
today to dramatize
to the nation

760
00:42:42,660 --> 00:42:44,628
and dramatize to
the wand

761
00:42:44,695 --> 00:42:47,960
that hundreds
and thousands of
Negro citizens

762
00:42:48,032 --> 00:42:50,057
are denied
the right to vote.

763
00:42:52,169 --> 00:42:55,036
I remember so well
on that particular day.

764
00:42:55,105 --> 00:42:58,040
We came to the highest point
on the bridge.

765
00:42:58,108 --> 00:43:01,134
Down below we saw
a sea of blue--

766
00:43:01,211 --> 00:43:03,509
Alabama State Troopers--

767
00:43:03,581 --> 00:43:05,310
and a man identified himself
and said,

768
00:43:05,382 --> 00:43:09,182
"I'm Major John Cloud of
the Alabama State Troopers.

769
00:43:09,253 --> 00:43:10,550
"This is an unlawful march.

770
00:43:10,621 --> 00:43:12,418
You will not be allowed
to continue."

771
00:43:12,489 --> 00:43:14,354
CLOUD: This is
Major Cloud talking.

772
00:43:14,425 --> 00:43:16,484
Marching this way.

773
00:43:16,560 --> 00:43:19,552
JOHN LEWIS: You saw these guys
putting on their gas masks.

774
00:43:19,630 --> 00:43:20,961
[Crowd shouting]

775
00:43:22,166 --> 00:43:25,294
They came toward us...

776
00:43:25,369 --> 00:43:27,234
beating us with nightsticks.

777
00:43:41,919 --> 00:43:45,377
I was hit in the head by a State
Trooper with a nightstick.

778
00:43:45,456 --> 00:43:48,016
I thought I was going to die.
I thought I saw death.

779
00:43:49,994 --> 00:43:51,586
GATES: The brutality at Selma

780
00:43:51,662 --> 00:43:55,359
was broadcast on
national television.

781
00:43:55,432 --> 00:43:57,297
TV ANNOUNCER: Programs
normally seen at this time

782
00:43:57,368 --> 00:43:58,835
will not be broadcast.

783
00:43:58,902 --> 00:44:00,494
[Crowd shouting]

784
00:44:00,571 --> 00:44:04,132
GATES: 48 million people
across the country watched

785
00:44:04,208 --> 00:44:07,735
as peaceful protesters were
attacked by police

786
00:44:07,811 --> 00:44:10,746
with nightsticks and tear gas.

787
00:44:10,814 --> 00:44:12,406
John Lewis once said that

788
00:44:12,483 --> 00:44:14,542
with out television news
coverage,

789
00:44:14,618 --> 00:44:16,609
the civil rights movement
would have been

790
00:44:16,687 --> 00:44:18,484
like a bird without wings

791
00:44:18,555 --> 00:44:20,318
or a choir
with out a song.

792
00:44:20,391 --> 00:44:21,415
Do you think
that's fair?

793
00:44:21,492 --> 00:44:24,689
I think this fight
for righteousness,

794
00:44:24,762 --> 00:44:29,131
for justice, really for
the honor of the country--

795
00:44:29,199 --> 00:44:31,394
it would have been
a longtime

796
00:44:31,468 --> 00:44:33,333
for the movement
to succeed.

797
00:44:33,404 --> 00:44:35,838
Television
was the instrument

798
00:44:35,906 --> 00:44:41,105
that, to use
John Lewis' metaphor,

799
00:44:41,178 --> 00:44:43,510
had people hear
the choir.

800
00:44:43,580 --> 00:44:45,207
This is Highway
Number 80,

801
00:44:45,282 --> 00:44:48,012
Selma to Montgomery,
Alabama.

802
00:44:48,085 --> 00:44:52,579
Once our people
were totally and terribly
brutalized here...

803
00:44:52,656 --> 00:44:54,123
GATES: By transforming
the movement

804
00:44:54,191 --> 00:44:57,592
into a kind of televised
morality play,

805
00:44:57,661 --> 00:45:01,062
Dr. King was able to appeal
to people of faith

806
00:45:01,131 --> 00:45:02,655
across the country,

807
00:45:02,733 --> 00:45:05,224
many of whom began
to join his cause.

808
00:45:05,302 --> 00:45:06,894
[Crowd singing
"We Shall Overcome"]

809
00:45:06,970 --> 00:45:08,835
JOSEPH: What's extraordinary
about nonviolence

810
00:45:08,906 --> 00:45:11,841
is that nonviolence helps you
get the clergy leaders,

811
00:45:11,909 --> 00:45:15,845
whether Catholic, Protestant,
Jewish, Muslim--

812
00:45:15,913 --> 00:45:18,848
the kind of alliances
that were needed.

813
00:45:18,916 --> 00:45:22,181
GATES: After Bloody Sunday,
hundreds of clergy,

814
00:45:22,252 --> 00:45:27,246
including rabbis Marc Tanenbaum
and Abraham Joshua Heschel,

815
00:45:27,324 --> 00:45:31,090
came to Selma
in a show of unity.

816
00:45:31,161 --> 00:45:36,030
The people, most of
whose names were
barely known at the time

817
00:45:36,100 --> 00:45:38,967
and long since
forgotten, who took pan

818
00:45:39,036 --> 00:45:43,405
in the nonviolent
protests--

819
00:45:43,474 --> 00:45:45,135
they made the civil
rights movement.

820
00:45:50,581 --> 00:45:53,482
GATES: The outrage following
the brutality in Selma

821
00:45:53,550 --> 00:45:58,044
incited demonstrations in over
80 cities across America.

822
00:45:59,656 --> 00:46:03,057
Once again, the treatment
of its black citizens

823
00:46:03,127 --> 00:46:06,585
was becoming a liability
to a nation trying to be

824
00:46:06,663 --> 00:46:10,793
the face of democracy
around the wand.

825
00:46:10,868 --> 00:46:14,065
The South was a national
embarrassment.

826
00:46:14,138 --> 00:46:18,006
Congress and the White House
were compelled to act.

827
00:46:18,075 --> 00:46:21,272
JOHNSON: It's not
just Negroes but really

828
00:46:21,345 --> 00:46:26,009
it's all of us who must overcome

829
00:46:26,083 --> 00:46:32,682
the crippling legacy of bigotry
and injustice.

830
00:46:32,756 --> 00:46:36,157
GATES: March 15, 1965.

831
00:46:36,226 --> 00:46:40,185
President Lyndon Baines Johnson
astonished the nation

832
00:46:40,264 --> 00:46:42,732
by invoking the phrase that had
become the mantra

833
00:46:42,800 --> 00:46:44,495
of the movement.

834
00:46:44,568 --> 00:46:47,560
And we sh all overcome.

835
00:46:47,638 --> 00:46:48,662
[Applause]

836
00:46:48,739 --> 00:46:50,434
GATES: I watched that speech
in our living room

837
00:46:50,507 --> 00:46:54,204
on our little black-and-white TV
with my parents.

838
00:46:54,278 --> 00:46:55,768
JOHNSON: And the long denial...

839
00:46:55,846 --> 00:46:59,179
GATES: Even then, at that age,
tears came to my eyes.

840
00:46:59,249 --> 00:47:01,809
A few months later,
President Johnson would sign

841
00:47:01,885 --> 00:47:04,410
our nation's first
Voting Rights Act.

842
00:47:04,488 --> 00:47:07,355
Just 10 years following
the Montgomery bus boycott,

843
00:47:07,424 --> 00:47:09,221
a revolution had occurred.

844
00:47:09,526 --> 00:47:11,494
[Applause]

845
00:47:12,830 --> 00:47:14,889
GATES: The passage
of the Voting Rights Act

846
00:47:14,965 --> 00:47:18,162
was the high water mark of
a decade of struggle

847
00:47:18,235 --> 00:47:19,793
for civil rights.

848
00:47:22,439 --> 00:47:24,703
But despite the
legislative victory,

849
00:47:24,775 --> 00:47:28,142
southern states still made it
difficult if not impossible

850
00:47:28,212 --> 00:47:29,839
for black citizens

851
00:47:29,913 --> 00:47:32,074
to register and vote.

852
00:47:34,818 --> 00:47:39,812
In June 1966, James Meredith,
a law student,

853
00:47:39,890 --> 00:47:42,791
staged a solo march
across the South

854
00:47:42,860 --> 00:47:46,352
to draw attention to the issue
of voter registration.

855
00:47:46,430 --> 00:47:49,558
It would be called
The March Again st Fear.

856
00:47:51,802 --> 00:47:54,464
Barely two days into his march,

857
00:47:54,538 --> 00:47:57,837
Meredith crossed
the Mississippi state line...

858
00:47:57,908 --> 00:47:59,466
[Gunshot]

859
00:47:59,543 --> 00:48:02,740
And was shot and wounded
by a sniper.

860
00:48:06,116 --> 00:48:08,141
In the days following
the shooting,

861
00:48:08,218 --> 00:48:11,619
the movement's elders,
led by Dr. King,

862
00:48:11,688 --> 00:48:15,021
came to finish what
James Meredith had started.

863
00:48:16,260 --> 00:48:19,491
But this time, they were joined
by SNCC

864
00:48:19,563 --> 00:48:23,090
and its youthful leader
Stokely Carmichael.

865
00:48:23,166 --> 00:48:24,326
JOSEPH: You have two
generations:

866
00:48:24,401 --> 00:48:27,131
the generation that Martin
Luther King Jr. represents

867
00:48:27,204 --> 00:48:30,230
and the generation that
Stokely Carmichael represents,

868
00:48:30,307 --> 00:48:33,538
and Dr. King's message was
really wearing thin

869
00:48:33,610 --> 00:48:35,601
in this latter half
of the 1960s,

870
00:48:35,679 --> 00:48:39,376
particularly because
there's so much violence.

871
00:48:39,449 --> 00:48:42,213
FORBES: As the violence grew,

872
00:48:42,286 --> 00:48:48,748
the willingness
to be passive declined.

873
00:48:48,825 --> 00:48:51,225
MIKE WALLACE: Do you think
you'll be able to keep it
nonviolent, Dr. King?

874
00:48:51,295 --> 00:48:52,387
Yes, I think so.

875
00:48:52,462 --> 00:48:55,625
I don't have any doubt
in my mind about that.

876
00:48:55,699 --> 00:48:56,927
WALLACE: Mr. Carmichael,
are you as committed

877
00:48:57,000 --> 00:48:58,729
to the nonviolent approach
as Dr. King is?

878
00:48:58,802 --> 00:48:59,734
No, I'm not.

879
00:48:59,803 --> 00:49:01,168
Why aren't you?

880
00:49:01,238 --> 00:49:02,637
Well, I just don't
see it as a way
of life.

881
00:49:02,706 --> 00:49:04,037
I never have.

882
00:49:04,107 --> 00:49:06,473
JOSEPH: The Meredith march is
where Stokely Carmichael

883
00:49:06,543 --> 00:49:08,408
becomes an icon.

884
00:49:08,478 --> 00:49:09,809
No one in this
country is asking

885
00:49:09,880 --> 00:49:10,847
the white community
in the South

886
00:49:10,914 --> 00:49:12,677
to be nonviolent,

887
00:49:12,749 --> 00:49:13,943
and that in a sense
is giving them

888
00:49:14,017 --> 00:49:17,248
a free license to go
ahead and shoot us
at Mil.

