00:49:33,603 --> 00:49:34,661
What do you want?

897
00:49:34,738 --> 00:49:36,000
CROWD: Freedom!

898
00:49:36,073 --> 00:49:37,301
MAN: What do you want?

899
00:49:37,374 --> 00:49:38,739
CROWD: Freedom!

900
00:49:38,809 --> 00:49:39,776
MAN: When do you want it?

901
00:49:39,843 --> 00:49:40,775
CROWD: Now!

902
00:49:40,844 --> 00:49:41,833
MAN: How much of it
do you want?

903
00:49:41,912 --> 00:49:43,743
CROWD: All of it!

904
00:49:43,814 --> 00:49:46,977
MAN:That tells me that you're
gonna march with us,

905
00:49:47,050 --> 00:49:48,984
and we're gonna...

906
00:50:05,068 --> 00:50:06,296
MAN: We're here in the heart
of the black community

907
00:50:06,370 --> 00:50:08,497
in Greenwood in the deep
pan of Mississippi.

908
00:50:08,572 --> 00:50:09,698
The tensions
within the march

909
00:50:09,773 --> 00:50:12,367
are starting to manifest
themselves.

910
00:50:12,442 --> 00:50:14,000
Twilight was coming.

911
00:50:14,077 --> 00:50:17,012
This park is filled
with the Meredith
marchers.

912
00:50:18,949 --> 00:50:20,974
Stokely Carmichael gets
up to give a speech.

913
00:50:21,051 --> 00:50:22,575
CARMICHAEL: We've begged
the federal government.

914
00:50:22,652 --> 00:50:24,677
That's all we've been doing:
begging, begging.

915
00:50:24,755 --> 00:50:26,313
It's time we stand up
and take over.

916
00:50:26,390 --> 00:50:27,322
[Crowd cheers]

917
00:50:27,391 --> 00:50:29,382
CARMICHAEL: Take over.

918
00:50:29,459 --> 00:50:30,483
He talks about
black aspirations.

919
00:50:30,560 --> 00:50:32,824
He talks about how
black is beautiful.

920
00:50:32,896 --> 00:50:33,885
And he talks about
how black people

921
00:50:33,964 --> 00:50:35,795
need to control
their own communities.

922
00:50:35,866 --> 00:50:37,561
Every courthouse
in Mississippi

923
00:50:37,634 --> 00:50:39,192
ought to be burned
down tomorrow...

924
00:50:39,269 --> 00:50:41,237
GOUDSOUZIAN: So that
when he drops the slogan,
if you will,

925
00:50:41,304 --> 00:50:42,430
when he
starts to say...

926
00:50:42,506 --> 00:50:43,564
CARMICHAEL:
What do you want?

927
00:50:43,640 --> 00:50:44,664
GOUDSOUZIAN:
What do we want?
Black power.

928
00:50:44,741 --> 00:50:45,969
CROWD: Black power!

929
00:50:46,043 --> 00:50:48,341
CARMICHAEL:
We want black power.

930
00:50:48,412 --> 00:50:50,039
We want black power.

931
00:50:50,113 --> 00:50:51,410
GOUDSOUZIANI
And starts
urging on the crowd,

932
00:50:51,481 --> 00:50:52,413
and the next thing
you know,

933
00:50:52,482 --> 00:50:53,744
he's got this
massive response.

934
00:50:53,817 --> 00:50:55,580
CROWD: Black power!
CARMICHAEL: What do you want?

935
00:50:55,652 --> 00:50:57,620
GOUDSOUZIAN:
That's a turning point
in African American history,

936
00:50:57,687 --> 00:50:59,279
and certainly
a turning point
in the civil rights movement.

937
00:50:59,356 --> 00:51:01,347
GATES: I saw it
that night on TV...

938
00:51:01,425 --> 00:51:02,357
Really?

939
00:51:02,426 --> 00:51:03,358
With my mother
and my father. Yeah.

940
00:51:03,427 --> 00:51:04,359
What did it
feel like?

941
00:51:04,428 --> 00:51:05,360
Oh, it was
electric, man.

942
00:51:05,429 --> 00:51:07,488
It was-l got
gooseﬂesh.

943
00:51:07,564 --> 00:51:09,054
You knew that--
it was like
the top of your head

944
00:51:09,132 --> 00:51:10,360
was about to
come off.

945
00:51:10,434 --> 00:51:12,664
Activists had expressed
a lot of these
ideas already,

946
00:51:12,736 --> 00:51:13,668
but black power-

947
00:51:13,737 --> 00:51:14,669
Not in my
living room.

948
00:51:14,738 --> 00:51:16,000
[Both laugh]

949
00:51:16,073 --> 00:51:17,404
I never heard it
before.

950
00:51:17,474 --> 00:51:19,305
I went, like,
"Whoa, man!"

951
00:51:19,376 --> 00:51:21,867
I'm like
a nuclear bomb
gone up.

952
00:51:21,945 --> 00:51:23,879
Black power [indistinct]

953
00:51:23,947 --> 00:51:25,608
Yeah!

954
00:51:25,682 --> 00:51:28,583
JOSEPH: By the next morning,
the whole nation

955
00:51:28,652 --> 00:51:29,744
is talking about black power.

956
00:51:35,792 --> 00:51:37,419
MAN: It was like
the great last march

957
00:51:37,494 --> 00:51:40,156
of these great
civil rights leaders.

958
00:51:41,598 --> 00:51:44,294
And because of that dynamic
going on

959
00:51:44,367 --> 00:51:47,336
between the different parts
of the movement,

960
00:51:47,404 --> 00:51:51,238
there emerged, like it was a
process, emerged a new movement.

961
00:51:51,308 --> 00:51:53,742
The new movement was
a black consciousness,

962
00:51:53,810 --> 00:51:55,505
black power movement

963
00:51:55,579 --> 00:51:58,980
which was not just political,
but it was a psychological

964
00:51:59,049 --> 00:52:01,540
break from the past
and saying,

965
00:52:01,618 --> 00:52:04,781
"We are moving to a new day,
a new change,

966
00:52:04,855 --> 00:52:07,756
and we're gonna do it
on our terms."

967
00:52:19,069 --> 00:52:23,233
KING: Like anybody, I would
like to live a long life.

968
00:52:23,306 --> 00:52:27,640
Longevity has its place.

969
00:52:27,711 --> 00:52:30,805
But I'm not concerned
about that now.

970
00:52:30,881 --> 00:52:36,183
GATES: Nonviolent protest seemed
to have run its course.

971
00:52:36,253 --> 00:52:42,385
The final tragic blow came
on April 4, 1968.

972
00:52:43,493 --> 00:52:45,723
And I've seen...

973
00:52:45,795 --> 00:52:46,727
the promised land.

974
00:52:46,796 --> 00:52:48,195
[Crowd murmuring]

975
00:52:48,265 --> 00:52:50,529
I may not get there with you...

